@article{myers2003bounds,
  abstract = {Recombination is an important evolutionary factor in many organisms, including humans, and under-
standing its effects is an important task facing geneticists. Detecting past recombination events is thus
important; this article introduces statistics that give a lower bound on the number of recombination events
in the history of a sample, on the basis of the patterns of variation in the sample DNA. Such lower bounds
are appropriate, since many recombination events in the history are typically undetectable, so the true
number of historical recombinations is unobtainable. The statistics can be calculated quickly by computer
and improve upon the earlier bound of Hudson and Kaplan (1985). A method is developed to combine
bounds on local regions in the data to produce more powerful improved bounds. The method is flexible
to different models of recombination occurrence. The approach gives recombination event bounds between
all pairs of sites, to help identify regions with more detectable recombinations, and these bounds can be
viewed graphically. Under coalescent simulations, there is a substantial improvement over the earlier
